M|Fail|**Sy|** Team keeps building w/o measuring. "Just one more feature and then we will launch."
M|Fail|fix|** Enforce a maximum bd time-box of 2 weeks. If you cannot tst a hypothesis in 2 weeks of building, the hypothesis is too big. Break it down.
M|Fail|**Sy|** Every loop "succeeds" bc the team measures page views, downloads, or sign-ups w/o connecting to value creation.
M|Fail|fix|** Every experiment must have an actionable metric w/ a pre-set decision threshold. If the metric goes up but does not change your nx action, it is vanity.
M|Fail|**Sy|** The Learn phase stretches for weeks. Team debates data endlessly w/o deciding.
M|Fail|fix|** Schedule the decision meeting before the experiment starts. Use pre-set criteria. If the data is ambiguous, run the experiment again w/ a larger sample or clearer metric, but decide that within one day.
M|Fail|**Sy|** Team interprets all data as supporting their original idea. Pivots never happen.
M|Fail|fix|** Assign a "devil's advocate" for every Learn sn. Write down what data wld cause you to abandon the idea before you see the data. Have someone outside the team rv the results.
M|Fail|**Sy|** Team runs one experiment, declares sc, and shifts to full-scale dv.
M|Fail|fix|** A single experiment validates a single assumption. Most pd have 5-15 ct assumptions. Plan a sequence of loops, each targeting a different assumption.
M|Fail|**Sy|** The team runs experiments but cannot recall what they learned three months ago. Same hypotheses get retested.
M|Fail|fix|** Maintain an experiment log (spreadsheet or wiki). Every experiment card gets archived w/ results. rv the log at the start of each new loop.
M|Para|tx|Run multiple experiments simultaneously when they tst independent assumptions. A team of 6 can often run 2-3 concurrent loops if the assumptions do not depend on each other.
M|Para|**Wh|**
M|Para|it|Assumptions are independent (result of one does not affect another)
M|Para|it|Team has bandwidth w/o context-switching overhead
M|Para|it|Each loop has a dedicated owner
M|Para|**Wh|**
M|Para|it|Assumptions are sequential (must validate A before B makes sense)
M|Para|it|Team is small (fewer than 4 people)
M|Para|it|Results from one experiment change the ds of another
M|Comp|Tech|
M|Comp|tx|\| Technique \| How It Works \| Best For \|
M|Comp|tx|\|-----------\|-------------\|----------\|
M|Comp|tx|\| Five-second tests \| Show a ds for 5 seconds, ask what it communicates \| Value proposition clarity \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Fake door tests \| Add a button/link for an unbuilt feature, measure clicks \| Feature demand validation \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Concierge MVP \| Deliver the service manually to 5-10 cs \| Service-based hypotheses \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Painted door w/ survey \| After click, explain feature is coming and ask 3 questions \| Qualitative + quantitative signal \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Pre-sell \| Charge money before the pd exists \| Willingness-to-pay validation \|
M|Loop|Esta|
M|Loop|it|**Weekly loops** for early-stage, pre-pd-mk-fit teams
M|Loop|it|**Bi-weekly loops** for teams w/ an existing pd testing new features
M|Loop|it|**Monthly loops** for hardware or complex B2B pd w/ longer sales cycles
M|Loop|tx|The cadence creates accountability. Every loop has a start date and an end date. Missing the cadence is a signal that scope is too large or the team needs help.
M|Loop|tx|\| Level \| Description \| Loop Time \| Characteristics \|
M|Loop|tx|\|-------\|-------------\|-----------\|-----------------\|
M|Loop|tx|\| 1 - Ad hoc \| No formal process \| 2-3 months \| Experiments happen accidentally \|
M|Loop|tx|\| 2 - Aware \| Team understands the concept \| 4-6 weeks \| Experiments are planned but not systematic \|
M|Loop|tx|\| 3 - Practicing \| Regular loop cadence \| 2-3 weeks \| Hypotheses documented, decisions data-informed \|
M|Loop|tx|\| 4 - Proficient \| Parallel loops, pre-set criteria \| 1-2 weeks \| Team challenges its own assumptions proactively \|
M|Loop|tx|\| 5 - Mastery \| Loops are second nature \| 3-7 days \| Continuous experimentation culture, institutional learning \|
M|Loop|tx|Most teams start at Level 1 or 2. Reaching Level 3 is a sig milestone. Levels 4 and 5 typically require organizational support, tooling, and cultural commitment.